Ubuntu 22
zkapp: 0.21.5

I follow the tutorial: https://docs.minaprotocol.com/zkapps/writing-a-zkapp/introduction-to-zkapps/testing-zkapps-lightnet. When I use zk config --lightnet, terminal said Error: Mina GraphQL endipoint http://127.0.0.1:8000/graphql is not abaliable.
To make this endpoint available, you should start the Docker and then run `zk lightnet start`
Yes, I already use zk lightnet start --no-archive

Hello, I got same problem, 2024/08/09 09:56:29 [error] 147#147: *1 connect() failed (111: Connection refused) while connecting to upstream, client: 172.17.0.1, server: localhost, request: "POST /graphql HTTP/1.1", upstream: "http://127.0.0.1:3085/graphql", host: "localhost:8080"
background: no process found

I try to use zk lightnet start or docker run -it   --env NETWORK_TYPE="single-node"  --env PROOF_LEVEL="full"   --env LOG_LEVEL="Info"   -p 3085:3085  -p 5433:5432  -p 8080:8080 -p 8181:8181 -p 8282:8282 o1labs/mina-local-network:master-latest-lightnet
Anyone got a working version of the image
@Serhii
You can try to debug what is going on with the help of `--debug` CLI option available to every lightnet sub-command.
This error in Docker container output is harmless and is thrown by Nginx attempting to establish reverse proxy connection to the endpoint which is not yet available.

But another problems is inability to start daemon. `zk lightnet ...` has options to save container's services logs (like Mina daemon for instance) to debug issues. 
I think with your command you will see in Mina daemon logs something like "passed proof level doesn't match one the daemon was compiled with".
Essentially you cannot use "full" proving level with the images that has suffix `-lightnet`. You have to use `-devnet` one.
So, to make it work for you with `full` proof level, the command might look like the following: `zk lightnet start --type real --proof-level full`.

If `zk config --lightnet` fails it simply means that the Mina daemon is not available for any possible reasons. 
Try `zk lightnet stop` and then `zk lightnet start --debug` to see if there are any issues. Once command completes you can check the daemon's GQL endpoint availability by simple HTTP GET request to `http://localhost:8080/graphql`.
thank you seems to work with o1labs/mina-local-network:compatible-latest-devnet image
@Serhii is it possible to configure time between block production

It might be possible in nearest future with upcoming daemon configuration updates which, among other things, will allow us override daemon’s configs using runtime config (including current compile time configuration).
okay, I use lightnet to speedup my test but finally it will be like the devnet xd
What do you mean? Do you need time between block as devnet has or you want an ability to configure it yourself?

like you said the ability to configure it myself, I tested my smarcontract locally with proof and it works fine, but once deployed on mina testnet I got some proof errors, I need like 30 - 60 min to test my contract on testnet, so each time I want to test a new version I need lot of time to redeploy everything

my goal is to have similar environnement than testnet but with less time between blocks

There is also request on o1js github for this
https://github.com/o1-labs/o1js/pull/1784#issuecomment-2265125277
Talking about testing speed. Is there a way to run lightnet with proving disabled? Kind of like with local blockchain
This is default behaviour.

The whole idea behind the lightnet is to reflect mainnet/devnet as much as possible but be much faster and not resources demanding at the same time. Default behaviour will give you blocks with txns every ~20 seconds.

Moreover, time between blocks is not a matter of simple one variable, it is a bit more complicated. Because loads of empty blocks are useless and it is not simple (if possible at all) to make it include txns in every block that is produced, say, every second.
Back then we identified that lightnet configuration will give us more or less stable blocks every 20-30-40 seconds with ~8 txn in every block.
Less than 1 minute it’s already a good thing for me
This is the config im talking about https://github.com/MinaProtocol/mina/blob/develop/src/config/lightnet.mlh
